</ul>
<div class="d-panels font-secondary-light">
<div id="aip_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div class="p" id="A1">
<sup>1</sup>National Eye Institute, National Institutes of Health, Bethesda, MD USA</div>
<div id="A2">
<sup>2</sup>Oregon Health &amp; Science University, Portland, OR, USA</div>
<div class="author-notes p"><div class="fn" id="CR1">
<sup>✉</sup><p class="display-inline"><strong>Corresponding Author</strong>: Goetz, Kerry E., p: (301) 605-5635, <span>kerry.goetz@nih.gov</span></p>
</div></div>
</div>
<div id="anp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="notes p"><section id="historyarticle-meta1" class="history"><p>Issue date 2022 Nov 1.</p></section></div></div>
<div id="clp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="p"><a href="/about/copyright/" class="usa-link">PMC Copyright notice</a></div></div>
</div>
<div>PMCID: PMC9555870  NIHMSID: NIHMS1817529  PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36206110/" class="usa-link">36206110</a>
</div>
<div class="ra xbox p" role="complementary" aria-label="Related or updated information about this article"><div>The publisher's version of this article is available at <a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/ICU.0000000000000889" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Curr Opin Ophthalmol</a>
</div></div>
</div></section></section><section aria-label="Article content"><section class="body main-article-body"><section class="abstract" id="ABS1"><h2>Abstract</h2>
<section id="S1"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Purpose of Review:</h3>
<p id="P1">This review highlights the artificial intelligence (AI), machine learning (ML), and deep learning (DL) initiatives supported by the National Institutes of Health (NIH) and the National Eye Institute (NEI) and calls attention to activities and goals defined in the NEI Strategic Plan as well as opportunities for future activities and breakthroughs in ophthalmology.</p></section><section id="S2"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Recent Findings:</h3>
<p id="P2">Ophthalmology is at the forefront of AI-based innovations in biomedical research that may lead to improvement in early detection and surveillance of ocular disease, prediction of progression, and improved quality of life. Technological advances have ushered in an era where unprecedented amounts of information can be linked that enable scientific discovery. However, there remains an unmet need to collect, harmonize, and share data in a machine actionable manner. Similarly, there is a need to ensure that efforts promote health and research equity by expanding diversity in the data and workforce.</p></section><section id="S3"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Summary:</h3>
<p id="P3">The NIH/NEI have supported the development AI-based innovations to advance biomedical research. The NIH/NEI have defined activities to achieve these goals in the NIH Strategic Plan for Data Science and the NEI Strategic Plan and have spearheaded initiatives to facilitate research in these areas.</p></section><section id="kwd-group1" class="kwd-group"><p><strong>Keywords:</strong> Artificial intelligence, data science, bioinformatics, National Institutes of Health, National Eye Institute</p></section></section><section id="S4"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Introduction</h2>
<p id="P4">The emergence of artificial intelligence (AI), together with an unprecedented growth in the volume, velocity, and variety of biomedical data, has and will continue to revolutionize biomedical research and clinical practice. AI is a computer science discipline directed towards computationally enabling tasks and mimicking problem-solving that would typically require human intelligence. AI encompasses two notable subfields: machine learning (ML) and deep learning (DL) (<a href="#F1" class="usa-link">Figure 1</a>). ML uses algorithms to create models to automate tasks without the need for humans to continually program. These models may self-improve and become more accurate with exposure to additional data. DL, a subfield of ML, comprises multiple (“deep”) layers of artificial neural networks, each made of connected perceptrons, or single unit artificial neurons modeled after the architecture of neurons in our brains. Together, technological advancements in AI, ML, and DL in parallel with the increased accessibility of large datasets have amplified scientists’ ability to translate research and theory into clinical practice.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F1"><h3 class="obj_head">Figure 1:</h3>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><img class="graphic" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7758/9555870/c12c4f5f0fbb/nihms-1817529-f0001.jpg" loading="lazy" height="457" width="1050" alt="Figure 1:"></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F1/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p id="P33">Description and relationship of Artificial Intelligence (AI), Machine Learning (ML), and Deep Learning (DL)</p></figcaption></figure><p id="P5">Given the growing opportunities for data-driven discovery using AI, the National Institutes of Health (NIH) have prioritized agency-wide initiatives to optimize data science ecosystems in a socially conscious and scientifically robust manner (<a href="#F2" class="usa-link">Figure 2</a>) [<a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a>]. The NIH places emphasis on a holistic approach to managing and utilizing “Big Data,” taking into consideration not only the development and implementation of AI technologies, but also training a diverse workforce, addressing ethical considerations of patient privacy, disparities in patient representation in datasets, and the potential for AI to mitigate those disparities when deployed thoughtfully. Currently, the NIH has several AI/ML initiatives underway across each of NIH’s 27 institutes, centers, and offices.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F2"><h3 class="obj_head">Figure 2:</h3>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><img class="graphic" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7758/9555870/7abfefa615d9/nihms-1817529-f0002.jpg" loading="lazy" height="318" width="1050" alt="Figure 2:"></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F2/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p id="P34">Timeline of important NIH and NEI activities in data science.</p>
<p id="P35">Abbreviations:</p>
<p id="P36">FDA: Food and Drug Administrations</p>
<p id="P37">NIH: National Institutes of Health</p>
<p id="P38">NEI: National Eye Institute</p>
<p id="P39">ACD: Advisory Council to the Director</p></figcaption></figure><p id="P6">Alongside vision researchers throughout the world, the National Eye Institute (NEI), one of the NIH institutes, has played leading roles from conception to implementation of AI-based innovations. Eye care is uniquely suited to AI due to the wide-spread use of imaging -a primary media for AI/ML/DL- as a diagnostic tool as well as the non-invasive accessibility of the eye. As a result, the field has been at the forefront of clinically applicable AI developments, which can lead to advances in disease detection and surveillance, patient specific prognostication, and improved quality of life.</p>
<p id="P7">As a result of advancements in both the computational and medical fields, the NEI has prioritized initiatives and infrastructures to further invest in these fields. The 2021-2015 NEI Strategic Plan calls attention to data science as a key area of emphasis across ocular scientific domains (<a href="#F3" class="usa-link">Figure 3</a>) [<a href="#R2" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R2">2</a>]. The NEI aims to target four aspects of data science to best position vision research for the future: big data, AI/ML, computational science, and workforce training and diversity. Here, we highlight ongoing AI/ML initiatives led and supported by the NIH and the NEI, detail aspects of the NEI Strategic Plan concerning data science, and discuss future directions and emerging trends in the eye care field.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F3"><h3 class="obj_head">Figure 3:</h3>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><img class="graphic" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7758/9555870/adb5311ceaa9/nihms-1817529-f0003.jpg" loading="lazy" height="429" width="1050" alt="Figure 3:"></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F3/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p id="P40">National Eye Institute diagram of Strategic Plan elements.</p></figcaption></figure><section id="S5"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">AI and Data Science Initiatives at the NIH</h3>
<p id="P8">In 2018 the NIH Director commissioned a Working Group of the Advisory Committee to the Director (ACD) on Artificial Intelligence. The group issued a report the following year with eight recommendations focused on creating flagship datasets that are ML-friendly, advancing ethics and consent practices for the use of ML in biomedicine, and increasing the number of people skilled in ML techniques for biomedical research [<a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3">3</a>].</p>
<p id="P9">Based on the working group report, the NIH commenced multiple AI initiatives to improve data science in biomedical research. AI is not feasible for many existing datasets due to overall data heterogeneity, including differences in collection techniques and standardization. Additionally, gaps in the AI and data science workforce diversity persists. Two initiatives, Bridge to Artificial Intelligence (Bridge2AI) and the Artificial Intelligence/Machine Learning Consortium to Advance Health Equity and Researcher Diversity (AIM-AHEAD) abandon the traditional hypothesis driven research approach to create data resources to address these gaps [<a href="#R4" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R4">4</a>,<a href="#R5" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R5">5</a>]. Bridge2AI sets out to generate AI/ML-ready datasets that contain comprehensive biomedical or behavioral data, develop software tools and standards, and enhance the workforce diversity and improve data science training. Data collected in a systematic and standardized way will allow scientists to harness the full power of AI to integrate information across data types (e.g., genomics, electronic health record (EHR), images, etc.). Systematically collected data can also establish new connections between different diseases and create an integrated biological resource. Ultimately, the availability of data collected with down-stream AI applications in mind from the onset can help accelerate biomedical discovery.</p>
<p id="P10">AIM-AHEAD also expands the availability of AI-ready datasets with special attention on ensuring diversity and equity in both the data and workforce. This program was established in 2021 to recruit and train a diverse workforce, increase the number of underrepresented researchers and research communities in AI based studies, and reduce biases in data available that may perpetuate disparities in research and health outcomes [<a href="#R5" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R5">5</a>]. AIM-AHEAD tackles these issues from multiple angles; it ensures that researchers have appropriate training programs and interdisciplinary networks, as well as data and computing infrastructure to meet these goals. Together, Bridge2AI and AIM-AHEAD address gaps of data readiness and data equity faced by the research community.</p>
<p id="P11">The availability of harmonized and interoperable data will provide scientists the opportunity to establish connections within and across disciplines, facilitating richer insights from existing datasets. Such discoveries are already underway. Recently, scientists identified patients at high risk for a cardiovascular event by using an AI system using linked patient clinical data and retinal images [<a href="#R6" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R6">6</a>]. Making data broadly available may provide scientists with the opportunity to combine smaller datasets to generate a larger dataset that can be used to meaningfully explore rare diseases [<a href="#R7" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R7">7</a>]. Furthermore, data equity and diversity can reduce existing biases in research datasets and methodologies, leading to a broader application of research results.</p></section><section id="S6"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Progress to Date: NEI Innovations in AI/ML for Vision Care</h3>
<section id="S7"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">AI Initiatives for Screening, Monitoring, and Diagnosing Eye Disease</h4>
<p id="P12">For years, the NEI has supported the development of numerous AI-based innovations to diagnose, monitor, and screen eye diseases, increase patient access to eye screenings, and improve patient quality of life. Amongst the AI-based innovations to diagnose and screen eye diseases are: EyeArt<sup>®</sup> and EyeStar, validated AI technologies for autonomous screening and detection of diabetic retinopathy (DR); IDx-DR, an AI system for diagnosing DR and macular edema; and i-ROP DL, an artificial intelligence algorithm for the detection of retinopathy of prematurity. Each of these devices help screen for and diagnose ocular disease with comparable or better accuracy compared to human screeners. The remarkable success and potential impact of many of these devices have been recognized by the FDA. In 2018, IDx-DR became the first FDA approved autonomous AI system to provide a diagnostic decision and in 2020 i-ROP was granted FDA breakthrough status[<a href="#R8" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R8">8</a>,<a href="#R9" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R9">9</a>].</p>
<p id="P13">The NEI is also utilizing AI to optimize product design. In a study on treating dry age-related macular degeneration (dry AMD) by replacing the dying retinal pigment epithelial (RPE) cell layer with patient-derived stem cells, an AI-based image analysis tool was developed to detect markers of RPE maturity and predict tissue function prior to implantation. In doing so, scientists can identify tissue samples with increased likelihood of successful integration, improve quality control, scale up tissue manufacturing, and accelerate delivery of stem cell derived RPEs to the clinic [<a href="#R10" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R10">10</a>]. In another study, scientists have used neural networks to develop retinal prosthetic devices with the aim of restoring functional vision for patients[<a href="#R11" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R11">11</a>].</p>
<p id="P14">The NEI also supports research efforts to advance the availability of disease monitoring devices. For example, clinician scientists recently validated the efficacy of monitoring wet AMD progression using the home-based, technician-free Notal Home OCT device. The device-captured OCT images are analyzed by a DL algorithm to detect fluid accumulation and disease progression; the algorithm detection was found to have a higher level of accuracy compared to retinal specialists [<a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">12</a>]. As another example, the NEI is funding a clinical study to validate glaucoma progression by assessing a patient’s visual field loss using NGoggle, a wearable device that utilizes virtual reality and embedded electroencephalogram sensors to monitor progression of disease [<a href="#R13" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R13">13</a>,<a href="#R14" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R14">14</a>]. Through such validation efforts, NEI is a partner in ensuring that technologies developed perform to a high standard.</p>
<p id="P15">Each of these examples highlights not only the technological capabilities of AI, but also the potential for new technologies to offer tremendous societal benefits by making eye screening and monitoring more accessible outside clinical settings. This reduces many of the barriers associated with delayed eye care, including delivery of screening resources to geographically underserved areas, the growing shortage of eye health providers, and patient-related factors (e.g., convenience, work-time constraints, insurance coverage) [<a href="#R15" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R15">15</a>]. These devices offer increased availability of screening and time of intervention to better support patient health, and at the same time allow providers to feel comfortable and confident relying on these tools following validation studies.</p>
<p id="P16">The early screening and detection of eye disease leads to early intervention, preserving functional vision status and protecting patient quality of life [<a href="#R16" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R16">16</a>,<a href="#R17" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R17">17</a>]. Beyond preventative measures, there are ongoing initiatives at the NEI to improve the quality of life of patients with existing visual impairment. The NEI co-funded the development of an advanced robotic cane to address gaps in functionality with existing canes [<a href="#R18" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R18">18</a>]. This cutting-edge technology integrates multiple data types (building floor plans, 3D color-depth cameras, inertial measurement sensors) to offer users sensory and auditory cues to help navigate unfamiliar spaces with safety and confidence. Outside of the NEI, other AI-enabled applications are being undertaken to assist individuals experiencing vision loss. For example, OneStep Reader is a multilingual mobile application that uses optical character recognition to convert text captured by a smartphone camera to speech or Braille, providing reading assistance to visually impaired people.</p>
<p id="P17">In addition to funding hypothesis-driven basic and clinical research projects, NEI has also funded innovative, non-traditional vision research making fundamental contributions to the data science and AI fields. For example, NEI has co-funded multidisciplinary investigators through a collaborative funding opportunity between NIH and the National Science Foundation (NSF), <em>Smart Health and Biomedical Research in the Era of Artificial Intelligence and Advanced Data Science (SCH) (NSF 21-530)</em>. The NEI is also an active participant and received funding support on several trans-NIH data science initiatives supported by the NIH Office of Data Science and Strategy. As the area of data science and AI continues to grow, we believe that the involvement and support by NEI will also increase in the coming years.</p>
<p id="P18">Furthermore, the NEI has played an active role supporting the development and growth of small businesses through NEI Small Business Grant Program. This grant provides two funding opportunities: the Small Business Innovation Research (SBIR) program, which funds projects led primarily by a single institution, and the Small Business Technology Transfer (STTR) program, which funds projects led by small businesses in collaboration with non-profit institutions. Annually, the NEI invests approximately $24 million in these programs, funding up to 80 grants each year. These grants also provide awardees access to technical assistance programs and expert consultants to support the commercialization process of innovative ocular devices and medications. The advancement of ONL1204 Ophthalmic Solution, a small peptide that delays cell death in patients with retinal detachment until surgical re-attachment can be performed, is one example of work supported by an NEI SBIR grant.</p>
<p id="P19">The development of these innovations is made possible by the characteristics that define ‘big data’: variety, velocity, and volume. Biomedical data includes information that can be obtained from electronic health records, genetics/genomic screening, other multi-omics datasets (e.g., eye tissues and cell types, single-cell RNA-Seq), ocular images (e.g., OCT images), visual functional data, and others. Data can also be patient derived, including those obtained from smart phones, home assistance devices, or patient reported outcomes. Despite availability of data, investments are needed in data storage, policies regarding data sharing including security and consent, and standardization across institutions. In efforts to address these gaps, the NIH has provided 38 awards for the development of AI-ready data and 24 awards to for the development and implementation of AI-related curricular or training activities in 2021 [<a href="#R19" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R19">19</a>,<a href="#R20" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R20">20</a>]; more awards are expected for the current fiscal year. The FAIR (Findable, Accessible, Interoperable, and Reusable) principles for data stewardship and data sharing have been adopted across NIH and a new data management and sharing resources are being developed [<a href="#R21" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R21">21</a>]. The NEI has also taken additional steps towards making data and resources available for secondary use establishing the NEI Data Commons (<a href="https://neidatacommons.nei.nih.gov/" class="usa-link" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">https://neidatacommons.nei.nih.gov/</a>), a publicly available central location for NEI applications and datasets, and the NEI GitHub (<a href="https://github.com/NIH-NEI" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">https://github.com/NIH-NEI</a>).</p></section><section id="S8"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">The Path Forward: The 2021-2025 NEI Strategic Plan</h4>
<p id="P20">The 2021-2025 NEI Strategic Plan was developed to best position the vision research community to capitalize on the technologic and computing advances in vision research and patient care. Input on priorities pertinent to the vision research community as well as strategies for implementation were obtained through public comment and scientific stakeholder panels. The 2021-2025 NEI Strategic Plan sets 5-year goals for the Institute and vision research community at large, provides a framework for investments, and guides operations.</p>
<p id="P21">This plan includes seven cross-cutting areas of emphasis including a chapter covering a strategic vision for data science with a focus on big data, AI, workforce and training, and computational advancements. Big data and AI have overlapping areas of unmet need and opportunities including the standardization of all aspects of data collection, from acquisition to processing to shared access. Data standardization can make data more usable by researchers and accelerates time from data acquisition to scientific discovery by reducing data processing burden while ensuring that context is preserved. The plan additionally aims to advance the integration and interoperability of data and AI systems. This plan suggests opportunities for research would be gained by increasing the accessibility and integration of different <em>types</em> of datasets (e.g., genomics, image, and EHR), to maximize the value obtained from clinical information.</p>
<p id="P22">Efforts towards achieving these goals must coincide with efforts to expand the data science workforce. The NEI is creating opportunities for training and expertise development, investing in intersection training amongst existing data scientists and data generators, creating opportunities for collaboration through scientific challenges and competition, and increasing workforce diversity. One way in which the NEI has taken action to meet this goal is by establishing an institute specific Diversity, Equity, Inclusion &amp; Accessibility Council. Additionally, the NEI recently launched two institutional offices, the NEI Office of Data Science and Health Informatics and the NEI Office of Vision Health and Population Sciences to achieve its mission statement.</p></section></section></section><section id="S9"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Conclusion</h2>
<p id="P23">The remarkable advances in clinical and computational science and their promise to impact scientific discovery, health equity, and quality of life is energizing. The developments described in this article highlight only a fraction of the innovative developments supported by the NIH in AI. NIH programs such as Bridge2AI and AIM-Ahead, and other funded research will address different challenges in the biomedical and vision research field, including more complex AI techniques, development of screening and diagnostic devices, clinical decision support, low-vision aids, and innovative treatment applications. The NIH and NEI are committed to continuing to increase the availability of AI-ready data, tools, and train the next generation of clinicians and data scientists to seek fundamental knowledge about the nature and behavior of living systems and the application of that knowledge to enhance health, improve quality of life, and reduce illness and disability.</p></section><section id="floats-group1" class="floats-group"><section class="bt xbox font-sm" id="BX1"><h2 class="obj_head">Key Points.</h2>
<ol id="L1" class="list" style="list-style-type:decimal">
<li><p id="P41">The NIH has launched several initiatives to increase the availability of AI-ready data.</p></li>
<li><p id="P42">The 2021-2025 NEI Strategic Plan identifies data science and AI as one of seven key areas of emphasis across all ophthalmic disciplines and diseases.</p></li>
<li><p id="P43">AI, standardized datasets, and data science in general have the potential to accelerate biomedical discovery and enhance patient care across populations.</p></li>
<li><p id="P44">The NIH is increasing investments in the research categories of data science and machine learning and artificial intelligence.</p></li>
<li><p id="P45">Several of the first AI-based devices for disease diagnosis have applications in eye care.</p></li>
</ol></section></section><section id="S10" class="ack"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Acknowledgements</h2>
